# ProxyGate — Complete Project Rules

---

## 1. What ProxyGate Is

ProxyGate is a cross-platform desktop GUI (Windows + Linux) that manages a reverse proxy.
Core promise: users never touch a config file. They fill in forms, the app generates
Traefik-compatible YAML under the hood and signals the proxy to reload.

### The fundamental routing model

ProxyGate has ONE public-facing IP address — e.g. 203.0.113.10.
Every domain the user wants to proxy points to this single IP in DNS (Cloudflare or otherwise).
ProxyGate reads the Host: header on every incoming HTTP request and routes it to the
correct service group. Multiple completely different services (Jellyfin, Plex, a web app,
an API) can all share the same public IP without conflict because the Host header
distinguishes them.

Analogy: A hotel has one street address. The receptionist reads your room number
(the Host header) and sends you to the right floor. Different guests, same front door.

---

## 2. Core Concepts

### Public IP
The single IP address ProxyGate listens on. This is the ONLY IP ever put in DNS.
Stored in app_settings as public_ip. Displayed prominently in the app topbar.

### Route
A rule that maps an incoming hostname + optional path prefix to a service group.

  SUBDOMAIN match: jellyfin.example.com       → jellyfin group
  PATH match:      example.com/api/*           → api group
  PATH match:      example.com/shop/*          → shop group

Multiple routes can share the same base domain with different path prefixes.
They all use the same ProxyGate IP — no conflict.

### Service Group
A named pool of one or more backend upstream IP:port pairs.
The group is the virtual destination for a route.
ProxyGate health-checks each upstream independently every 30 seconds.
If one upstream goes down, traffic automatically goes to the remaining healthy upstreams.
The domain never goes down as long as ProxyGate is up AND at least one upstream is healthy.

  jellyfin group:
    192.168.1.10:8096  UP  12ms
    192.168.1.11:8096  UP   9ms
    → round-robin between both

  plex group:
    192.168.2.10:32400  DOWN  skipped
    192.168.2.11:32400  UP    8ms
    → all traffic to .11 while .10 is down

The group has NO public IP. Cloudflare DNS points to ProxyGate's IP only.
The upstream IPs are private/internal — never in DNS, never exposed to the internet.

### Upstream
A single IP:port entry inside a service group.
Has its own health status, latency reading, and optional weight for weighted load balancing.

### Host Header Routing (how separation works)
Every HTTP/1.1 request includes a Host: header set by the browser to the domain the user typed.
Even though all requests arrive on the same IP:443, ProxyGate reads this header to decide
which route matches, and therefore which service group gets the request.
This is standard HTTP behaviour since RFC 2616 (1997). It is how every major reverse proxy works.

Example for two services on the same IP:
  Request A: GET / HTTP/1.1  Host: jellyfin.example.com  → jellyfin group
  Request B: GET / HTTP/1.1  Host: plex.example.com      → plex group
  Both arrive at 203.0.113.10:443. ProxyGate separates them by reading Host.

### Cloudflare DNS
User creates A records in Cloudflare:
  jellyfin.example.com  A  203.0.113.10
  plex.example.com      A  203.0.113.10

Both point to the SAME IP. No conflict. Cloudflare only knows the one public IP.
ProxyGate does all the internal routing by Host header.

Cloudflare orange-cloud (proxy mode): when enabled, Cloudflare puts its CDN in front.
ProxyGate must then trust the CF-Connecting-IP header to get the real visitor IP.
ProxyGate auto-writes Cloudflare's IP ranges into forwardedHeaders.trustedIPs in the
generated Traefik config when the user enables "Cloudflare proxy mode" in settings.

### Path Stripping
When a route matches /api/*, the backend may expect requests at / not /api/.
Path stripping removes the prefix before forwarding.
Example: example.com/api/users → backend receives GET /users
Configurable per route with a toggle. Always show a before/after preview when enabled.

### Middleware
A plugin applied per-route via checkboxes when creating/editing a route.
Global enable/disable lives in the Middleware page.
Per-route middleware list is stored as a JSON array of middleware IDs on the route.

### TLS
ProxyGate terminates TLS. Backends are plain HTTP internally (no certs on backend servers).
Two modes:
  ACME: auto-issue and renew via Let's Encrypt. Requires ports 80+443 accessible.
  Manual: user uploads cert/key pair per domain.

